No—it isn’t, at least not entirely.

“Common sense” often gets treated as if it’s a fixed body of knowledge that everyone independently possesses. But much of what we call common sense is actually shared coordination that became invisible.

Children aren’t born knowing:

* to queue in line,
* to shake hands,
* that red means stop,
* that eye contact has social meaning,
* that “obviously” this expression means sarcasm.

Those are learned through repeated interaction until they feel self-evident.

So what we call common sense is often compressed social history.

It’s a shared cue system that has become so well established that we stop noticing it as a protocol.

Your point generalizes:

Many things we call “common sense” are simply highly stabilized shared cue mappings.

Not all of it. Some aspects of common sense are grounded in the physical world—don’t touch fire, falling objects accelerate downward, hungry people seek food. But a large portion of social common sense emerges from repeated coordination among people until the mapping becomes automatic.

Viewed that way, common sense isn’t just knowledge.

It’s the successful convergence of countless cue → interpretation → behavior loops across a community.

By the time it becomes “common sense,” everyone has forgotten that it was ever negotiated.